 Nation at a Glance

 Indian killed by Taliban identified

 New Delhi (PTI): The Indian killed in a Taliban bomb blast in Afghanistan on Tuesday has been identified as K. Bharath Kumar, a project engineer working with an American construction company. 

 The Indian embassy in Kabul is trying to retrieve his body from the western province of Farah. 

 The second Indian to be killed in terror violence in Afghanistan in the last two months, Kumar was working on the construction of a highway between Kandahar and Herat provinces, official sources said here on Wednesday. 

 He had been an employee of the US firm Louis Berger since August 15, 2005, they said.

 Besides Kumar, a Turkish national, a Nepalese guard and a local were also killed when a remote-controlled mine blew up their vehicle in Farah province. The Taliban has claimed responsibility for the blast. 

 Institute told to refund fees

 New Delhi (PTI): Coming down heavily on private educational institutions policy of fees once received not refundable, a consumer court has asked the Birla Institute of Management Technology (BIMT) to cough up Rs 44,000 as refund and compensation to a student.

 Merely because the seat could not be filled up does not mean that BIMT had a right to forfeit the amount of tuition fees and any such term which is against the public policy and good conscience is not valid and cannot be allowed to operate, said the Delhi state consumer disputes redressal commission.

 Dheeraj Sachdeva took admission in BIMT but could not pursue his studies there. 

 The court has asked the institute to pay Rs 5,000 as compensation, in addition to Rs 39,000 as the tuition fees, within a month.

 Rehab rights

 New Delhi: The Supreme Court has ruled that encroachers cannot claim the right to rehabilitation even if the government promises such a scheme, reports our legal correspondent. 

 They can claim it only if the state takes a policy decision under the stipulated constitutional provisions, the court said, dismissing a plea by milkmen from Bhubaneswar.

 Bofors case

 New Delhi (PTI): Delhi High Court will on February 17 take up a petition seeking the dismissal of solicitor-general G.E. Vahanvati and additional solicitor-general B. Dutta. The petition, filed by the Rashtriya Mukti Morcha, accused the duo of connivance in facilitating defreezing of Ottavio Quattrocchis London bank accounts.

 Boy to be freed

 Faridkot (PTI): An 11-year-old Pakistani boy, lodged at a juvenile home in this Punjab town, will be repatriated on Monday.

The Akhil Bhartiya Tirtha Purohit Parishad, a Hindu priests organisation in Mathura, will soon issue photo-identity cards to its members to prevent touts from fleecing pilgrims.




